Create a simple webpage illustrating the CSS Box Model

Develop a basic HTML page containing a single <div> element with text inside it. Apply CSS to showcase the different parts of the Box Model (content-box, padding, border, and margin). Set distinct colors for padding, border, and margin so that each is visually distinguishable. For example, use padding: 20px, border: 5px solid blue, and margin: 30px. Ensure that each part of the Box Model is clearly visible when the page is rendered.
Objective:

Learn to identify and manipulate the content, padding, border, and margin layers using CSS.
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>CSS Box Model Example</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
  <h1>CSS Box Model</h1>
  <div class="box">
    This is a box with visible padding, border, and margin.
  </div>
</body>
</html
/* Global styles */
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  text-align: center;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

h1 {
  margin-top: 20px;
  color: #333;
}

/* Box Model styles */
.box {
  width: 300px;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 5px solid blue;
  margin: 30px;
  
  /* Content-box is the default, so we don't need to specify it, but we'll include it for clarity */
  box-sizing: content-box;
  
  background-color: #ffeb3b; /* Background color of the content area */
  color: #333;
  font-size: 18px;
  text-align: center;
}

/* Visual demonstration of padding, border, and margin */
.box {
  /* Padding color (inside the content area) */
  padding: 20px;
  background-color: #ffeb3b;
  border: 5px solid blue;
}

.box:before {
  content: "Padding (20px)";
  display: block;
  margin-top: 10px;
  color: green;
}

.box:after {
  content: "Border (5px solid blue)";
  display: block;
  margin-top: 10px;
  color: blue;
}
